'''GD 61''' is a [[white dwarf]] with a planetary system located 150 light-years from Earth in the constellation [[Perseus (constellation)|Perseus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencenews.org/article/water-seen-rubble-around-star|title=Water seen in rubble around star
|date=13 October 2013|accessdate=14 October 2013|author=Rosen, Meghan|work=ScienceNews}}</ref> It is thought to have been a main-sequence star of spectral type A0V with around three times the mass of the Sun that has aged and passed through a [[red giant|red-giant]] phase, leaving a dense, hot remnant that has around 70% of the Sun's mass and a surface temperature of 17,280 K. It is thought to be around 600 million years old, including both its life as a main-sequence star and as a white dwarf.<ref name="farihi">{{cite journal|author1=Farihi, J. |author2=Brinkworth, C. S. |author3=Gänsicke, B. T. |author4=Marsh, T. R. |author5=Girven, J. |author6=Hoard, D. W. |author7=Klein, B. |author8=Koester, D. |title=Possible Signs of Water and Differentiation in a Rocky Exoplanetary Body|journal=The Astrophysical Journal Letters|volume=728|issue=1|pages= L8-L13|bibcode=2011ApJ...728L...8F|doi=10.1088/2041-8205/728/1/L8|arxiv = 1101.0158 }}</ref> It has an apparent magnitude of 14.8.<ref name="xu"/> GD 61 was first noted as a potential degenerate star in 1965, in a survey of white-dwarf suspects by astronomers from the [[Lowell Observatory]] in Arizona.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Giclas, Henry L. |author2=Burnham, Robert |author3=Thomas, Norman Gene |date=1965|title=A list of white dwarf suspects I : special objects of small proper motion from the Lowell survey|journal=Bulletin / Lowell Observatory|volume=6|issue=6|pages=155–64|url=http://articles.adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-iarticle_query?1965LowOB...6..155G&amp;data_type=PDF_HIGH&amp;whole_paper=YES&amp;type=PRINTER&amp;filetype=.pdf|bibcode=1965LowOB...6..155G}}</ref>

In 2013, a circumstellar disk that resulted from the destruction of a water-rich asteroid was detected in close orbit around GD 61, which makes this the first detection of solid or liquid water on an [[wikt:extrasolar|extrasolar]] body. This asteroid would originally have been 26% water by mass, close to the water content of [[Ceres (dwarf planet)|Ceres]].<ref name=circumstellar>[https://arxiv.org/pdf/1310.3269.pdf Evidence for water in the rocky debris of a disrupted extrasolar minor planet]</ref> This evidence suggests that a planet, with a rocky surface similar to Earth's, may have existed in the past, with the asteroid thus being an artifact from this period, now possibly part of a debris field from the hypothetical planet's breakup. Such a planet would have had both a rocky surface and water, two key ingredients for life.<ref name=watery>{{cite web|url=http://phys.org/news/2013-10-watery-asteroid-dying-star-habitable.html |title=Watery asteroid discovered in dying star points to habitable exoplanets |publisher=Phys.org |date=10 October 2013 |accessdate=12 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mack |first=Eric |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-17938_105-57607077-1/newly-spotted-wet-asteroids-point-to-far-flung-earth-like-planets/ |title=Newly spotted wet asteroids point to far-flung Earth-like planets &#124; Crave - CNET |publisher=News.cnet.com |date=17 October 2011 |accessdate=12 October 2013}}</ref> The researchers used the [[Cosmic Origins Spectrograph]] on the Hubble Space Telescope to determine the elemental composition. The elements magnesium, silicon, iron, and oxygen were detected, all components of rocky planets, although the levels of oxygen were much higher than what could be accounted for. The lack of associated carbon left only one candidate for the oxygen excess—water.<ref name=watery/><!-- cites previous two sentences -->

