'''XJB-5-131''' is a synthetic [[antioxidant]]. In a [[model organism|mouse model]] of [[Huntington's disease]], it has been shown to reduce [[oxidative stress|oxidative damage]] to [[mitochondrial DNA]], and to maintain [[mitochondrial DNA]] copy number.<ref name="MyUser_Ncbi.nlm.nih.gov_April_27_2016c">{{cite journal |title= Targeting of XJB-5-131 to Mitochondria Suppresses Oxidative DNA Damage and Motor Decline in a Mouse Model of Huntington's Disease| pmid=23122961 | doi=10.1016/j.celrep.2012.10.001 | volume=2 | issue=5 | pmc=3513647 | journal=Cell Rep | pages=1137–42 | last1 = Xun | first1 = Z | last2 = Rivera-Sánchez | first2 = S | last3 = Ayala-Peña | first3 = S | last4 = Lim | first4 = J | last5 = Budworth | first5 = H | last6 = Skoda | first6 = EM | last7 = Robbins | first7 = PD | last8 = Niedernhofer | first8 = LJ | last9 = Wipf | first9 = P | last10 = McMurray | first10 = CT| year=2012 }}</ref> XJB-5-131 also strongly protects against [[ferroptosis]], a form of iron-dependent regulated cell death.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Krainz|first1=Tanja|last2=Gaschler|first2=Michael|last3=Lim|first3=Chaemin|last4=Sacher|first4=Joshua|last5=Stockwell|first5=Brent|last6=Wipf|first6=Peter|title=A Mitochondrial-Targeted Nitroxide Is a Potent Inhibitor of Ferroptosis|journal=ACS Central Science|date=September 7, 2016|doi=10.1021/acscentsci.6b00199|pmid=27725964|pmc=5043442|volume=2|issue=9|pages=653–659}}</ref>
